The study conducted by Clapp (2001) investigated the influence of solar radiation on O3, NO and NO2 concentrations as a function of NOx in rural and urban environments. Variations in O3 concentration at the global level influence O3 and NO2 concentrations at the local level, and consequently, the response of NO2 to NOx emission reduction is highly non-linear. In relation to the total concentrations of oxidants OX (Eq. 8, ppb unit), Clapp studied how this varies with NOx concentrations.8OX=O3+NO2.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left[OX\right]= \left[{O}_{3}\right]+ \left[{NO}_{2}\right].$$\end{document}

The plot of the OX parameter as a function of NOx showed a linear trend characterised by a positive intercept, indicating a value that is a function of the region under observation, and an upward slope representing local or primary NOx emissions. On the basis of this evidence, the authors identified two main contributions to diurnal concentrations of total oxidants: a regional (or background) contribution that is close to O3 and largely independent of NOx, and a local contribution that is correlated with (i) the primary contribution of local NOx emissions to local NO2, (ii) local oxidation of NO to NO2 by O2, and (iii) local emissions of some species, such as HONO that may contribute to the conversion of NO to NO2. The study yielded the following relationship (ppb unit):9OX=0.104NOx+31.1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
